    "summary": "The image displays a letter from an individual named Pete to an unspecified editor of Personne Administrator. The letter is dated May 2, 1993, and is addressed to \"The Editor\". It discusses the author's perspective on smoking policies in the workplace. The writer shares their experience with pressure to restrict or segregate smoking employees, stating that they considered implementing such policies but decided against it due to potential negative effects on the workforce. They also mention a vocal group of employees pushing for change and share their own experiences with the issue. The letter expresses skepticism about the economic benefits of anti-smoking measures and questions the motives behind them.",
    "corrected_text": "ogilvy & Mather Letter to the Editor of Personne} Administrator DRAFT pete 5/2/93 To the Editor: As the owner of a company with about 100 employees, I found Lewis Solmon's recent article, \"The other side of the smoking worker controversy,\" interesting. I'd like to share my own views, since I we had some experience with the issue. A small but vocal group of employees have pressured me to either ban smoking or to segregate smokers and nonsmokers. When they first approached me I considered the situation but, for several reasons, decided against any restrictions. First, implementing smoking policies would have required that I take action against good employees who have worked for me for quite some time. Second, to implement a smoking policy would have disrupted my company's work process, since, as in many offices, employees with similar skills and responsi- abilities work together. Furthermore, once I took a hard look at the situation, f dis- covered that the vast majority of my employees were neither aware of nor particularly interested in the problem. I have not read any of wets articles to which salmon referred nor have I considered the economic aspect of the argument on which Solmon's article was based. But common sense suggests that rearranging people, changing policies, implementing re~ strictions, and @iscupting my workforce won't save me money. Sincerely, 2 took 0027645",
